The primary management species for Como Lake are bluegill, channel catfish, and yellow perch. Northern pike are a secondary management species. Nothern pike were sampled above median levels for abundance, and have shown a significant increase in the last five years. The average northern pike sampled was 21.8 inches and 2.88 pounds. Approximately 10% of all individuals sampled were 26.0 inches or larger. Golden shiners were abundant and should provide a good forage base for the northern pike. Black crappie were sampled within the normal range for abundance and averaged 7.2 inches and 0.22 pounds (4.55 fish/pound). The bluegill population was low, but has received supplemental stocking of adults in fall of 2001. Yellow perch were sampled below median levels of abundance and averaged 7.6 inches in length. Black and yellow bullheads are present in near equal abundance.

ONE THREE YEAR OLD WALLEYE 16' LONG WAS NETTED ELECTROFISHING. NO OTHER WALLEYE WERE SAMPLED. THE LARGEMOUTH BASS CATCH WAS ABOVE THE LOCAL MEDIAN BY 8 TIMES. THESE WERE AGE GROUPS I-IV SHOWING FAST GROWTH. SOME SMALL SIZE YY BASS WERE SEINED. ONLY I AND II AGE BLUEGILLS WERE SAMPLED SHOWING AVERAGE GROWTH THE FIRST YEAR AND FAST GROWTH THE SECOND. BLUEGILL CATCH RATE WAS 1.5 TIMES THE LOCAL MEDIAN, HOWEVER, THAT WAS DOWN FROM A RATE OF 178.4/TRAPNET IN 1988 TO 38.8/TRAP- NET IN 1989. PSD DECLINED ALSO FROM 13.1% TO 5.2%. TWELVE YELLOW BULLHEADS AND TWO HYBRID SUNFISH WERE SAMPLED.

Como Lake is a shallow, 70 acre lake located in a highly developed urban watershed in the City of Saint Paul. Como Lake receives direct runoff from 22 storm sewers and water quality is generally very poor. The entire lake is encompassed by Como Park, a regional park managed by Saint Paul Parks and Recreation. A fishing pier is located on the south shore of the lake along with a small parking lot. During summer this area of the lake can experience heavy submersed aquatic vegetation growth that may impede fishing from the pier with all but topwater baits. Chemical control of nuisance algae blooms and mechanical control of nuisance rooted aquatic plants have been conducted periodically. Several areas around the lake are conducive to shore fishing and much of the shoreline has been restored in recent years with native plantings. There is no official boat ramp on the lake but carry on watercraft and electric motors are allowed to be used; paddleboats are available to rent as well.

Walleye are the primary management species on Como Lake and regular stocking occur in the spring and fall. Bluegill and Black Crappie were the most abundant species observed during this survey; average sizes for each species were, 4.4 inches and 6.1 inches respectively. Twelve Walleye were sampled in trapnets during this survey, with lengths ranging from 8.0 to 23 inches long. Black Bullhead were sampled in below average abundance for lakes like Como during this survey. Black Bullhead size and quality in Como Lake is above average when compared to most metro area lakes. The majority of the Black Bullheads ranged in size from 8.0 to 11.5 inches. Other species sampled in low abundance during this survey included Largemouth Bass, Yellow Perch, Pumpkinseed, Hybrid and Green sunfish.

Bluegills were very abundant, but no fish older than III+ were taken. Growth of bluegill was average. Largemouth bass were believed to be relatively abundant, as all age classes since the chemical rehabilitation in fall 1985 were represented. Largemouth bass reproduction was good as indicated by shoreline seining. Nine walleye from the 1986 stocking were sampled - growth of walleye was average for the area. Other species taken in low numbers included black bullhead, yellow bullhead, and yellow perch. The origin of the yellow perch was unknown.

Como Lake is a shallow eutrophic, 70 acre lake located in the City of Saint Paul. The entire lake is encompassed by Como Park, a regional park managed by Saint Paul Parks and Recreation. A fishing pier is located on the south shore of the lake along with a small parking lot. Several areas around the lake are conducive to shore fishing. There is not a public boat ramp on the lake but electric motors are allowed to be used for carry in water craft. An aeration system operated By Ramsey County is run during the winter months to prevent winterkill.

Daytime electrofishing was conducted on 5/12/2017. Catch rate and lengths were recorded for Largemouth Bass and Walleye only. The last time electrofishing was conducted was in a 1996 assessment where 11 Largemouth Bass and one Walleye were sampled. Largemouth Bass catch rate was 3.11/hour and a total of 3 small Largemouth Bass were sampled. Lengths ranged from 6.0 to 6.99 inches. Some other smaller yearling fish were observed during this assessment in water too shallow to run the electrofisher. Walleye catch rate was 12.45/hour and a total of 12 Walleye were observed. Walleye lengths ranged from 8.7 to 23.4 inches with a mean length of 12.88 inches.

Como Lake is a shallow, 70 acre lake located in the City of Saint Paul. The entire lake is encompassed by Como Park, a regional park managed by Saint Paul Parks and Recreation. A fishing pier is located on the south shore of the lake along with a small parking lot. During summer this area of the lake can experience heavy submerged aquatic vegetation growth that may impede fishing from the pier with all but topwater baits. Several areas around the lake are conducive to shore fishing and much of the shoreline has been restored in recent years with native plantings. There is not a boat ramp but electric motors are allowed to be used on the lake, and paddleboats are available to rent as well.

The primary management species on Como Lake are bluegill sunfish and channel catfish. Northern pike, though not managed for, were very abundant in the 2011 survey with nearly 50 fish caught during the survey. The average length and weight was approximately 23" and three pounds. The largest fish measured 30 inches, but most fish were in the 20" to 25" size range. Bluegill and black crappie were abundant, though of small size, 5.4 inches and 6.2 inches respectively. Walleye were stocked most recently in 2000 (230 yearlings), 2001 (3,022 fingerlings), 2010 (4 yearlings) and 2011 (3,567 fingerlings-6 adults). It is likely that the five fish sampled during this survey originated with those stockings. The fish measured between 19" and 24" long and averaged nearly three pounds.

Channel catfish have been stocked into Como Lake during the periods of 1996-2003 and 2007-2011. This survey sampled them in moderate abundance (19 total fish) which is the most sampled to date at Como Lake. These fish clustered into two groups, those under 13 inches long (N=14) and those over 19 inches long (N=4). One fish was partially consumed and therefore no measurement taken. The larger fish probably originated in the Sauk River near Cold Spring, Minnesota and have been netted and stocked into Como Lake since 2007. The smaller fish were all likely fish that have been purchased from a private fish hatchery and stocked into the lake.

Black bullhead and yellow bullhead were both sampled during this survey in moderate numbers and ranged in size from 6.8" to 12.6" long. Other species sampled during this survey included one largemouth bass (16.2" long), yellow perch (all fish measured less than eight inches,) Pumpkinseed sunfish, hybrid sunfish, white sucker and golden shiners.

PRESENT FISH POPULATION CONSISTS OF LARGEMOUTH BASS, WALLEYE, AND BLUEGILL. WALLEYE AND LARGE- MOUTH BASS NUMBER PER NET WERE FOUND IN HIGHER NUMBERS THAN THE STATEWIDE AND LOCAL MEDIANS. BLUEGILLS WERE FOUND IN NUMBERS JUST ABOVE THE MEDIAN. ALL FISH WERE STOCKED EARLIER THIS SEASON. BLUEGILLS WERE PRIMARILY SMALL ADULT MALES 6/LB. WALLEYE AND LARGEMOUTH BASS YEARLINGS AND LARGE- MOUTH BASS FRY WERE STOCKED.

FISH POPULATION WAS COMPOSED OF BLUEGILL, LARGE- MOUTH BASS, AND WALLEYE. ONE YELLOW BULLHEAD AND ONE HYBRID SUNFISH WERE CAPTURED. WALLEYE AND BASS WERE II AND III YEAR OLD FISH WITH GOOD GROWTH AND BOTH WERE SAMPLED IN NUMBERS WELL ABOVE THE STATE AND LOCAL MEDIANS. THE BLUEGILL II YEAR AGE GROUP REFLECTED A DYNAMIC GROWTH SPURT FOLLOW- ING A CHEMICAL REHABILITATION. THE GROWTH RATE OF THE OTHER ADULT BLUEGILLS SHOWED SLOW GROWTH. THESE WERE FISH TRANSFERRED FROM OTHER LAKES WITH A STUNTED BLUEGILL POPULATION. *SEE SPECIAL REGULATION ASSESSMENT LENGTH FRE- QUENCY DISTRIBUTION CHARTS FOR BLUEGILLS AND LAR- GE MOUTH BASS.

Como Lake is a shallow lake (9 foot maximum depth). An aeration system prevents winterkill of fish. The lake is located in St. Paul's very popular Como Park. The entire shoreline is city-owned. There is a fishing pier on the south side and several other spots to fish from shore. A paved walking path goes around the entire lake. Canoes and carry-in craft are allowed, as are electric motors, but there is no boat ramp. During the mid-summer, dense vegetation can make fishing difficult from shore or pier. Black bullhead, bluegill, and northern pike were the most abundant species sampled in this assessment. Bullhead abundance seems to be on the rise from low abundance in the 1990s. Lengths ranged from 5 to 12 inches, with most between 6 and 7 inches. Bluegill lengths ranged from 3 to 8 inches, with about 20% over 6 inches. Northern pike have flourished since the late 1990's and are abundant. Lengths sampled ranged from 16 to 32 inches, with 19 to 23 inches being the predominant size group. Walleyes were sampled in moderate numbers and were large - 17 to 22 inches. Black crappie abundance is low to moderate. Lengths ranged from 5.5 to 10.5 inches, with most between 6 and 7 inches. Very few yellow perch were sampled - they were 4.5 to 7.5 inches long. No largemouth bass or channel catfish were sampled. In the late 1980's and early 1990's an experimental regulation required release of bass less than 16 inches long. During that time, bass abundance was high, but the bass population has declined dramatically since the regulation expired in 1993. Channel catfish were stocked from 1996 to 2003, but abundance was never high and angler interest was low, so stocking was discontinued in 2004.

Como Lake is a shallow, 70 acre lake located in a highly developed urban watershed in the City of Saint Paul. Como Lake receives direct runoff from 22 storm sewers and water quality is generally very poor. The entire lake is encompassed by Como Park, a regional park managed by Saint Paul Parks and Recreation. A fishing pier is located on the south shore of the lake along with a small parking lot. During summer this area of the lake can experience heavy submersed aquatic vegetation growth that may impede fishing from the pier with all but topwater baits. Chemical control of nuisance algae blooms and mechanical control of nuisance rooted aquatic plants have been conducted periodically. Several areas around the lake are conducive to shore fishing and much of the shoreline has been restored in recent years with native plantings. There is no official boat ramp on the lake but carry on watercraft and electric motors are allowed to be used, paddleboats are available to rent as well.

The primary management species on Como Lake are Bluegill Sunfish and Channel Catfish. Northern Pike, though not managed for, were abundant in the 2016 survey. The largest pike measured 33 inches, but most fish were in the 20" to 25" size range. Bluegill and Black Crappie were the most abundant species observed during this survey, though of small size, 5.5 inches and 6.7 inches respectively. Walleye were stocked most recently in 2011 (3,567 fingerlings-6 adults), 2013 (476 fingerlings), 2014 (71,000 fry and 4,108 yearlings), 2015 (2,840 yearlings) and 2016 (903 yearlings). Only two Walleye were sampled in trapnets during this survey, the fish measured between 7.5" and 18"long. Channel Catfish have been stocked into Como Lake during the periods of 2007-2011, 2014 and 2015. This survey sampled them in moderate abundance (3 total fish). These fish ranged in size from 17 to 22 inches long. These fish probably originated in the Sauk River near Cold Spring, Minnesota and have been netted and stocked into Como Lake since 2007. Black Bullhead were sampled in high abundance during this survey. Black Bullhead size and quality in Como Lake is above average when compared to most metro area lakes. The majority of the Black Bullheads ranged in size from 7.5 to 9.5 inches. Other species sampled in low abundance during this survey included Yellow Perch, Pumpkinseed and Hybrid sunfish and golden Shiners.

PRESENT FISH POPULATION CONSISTS OF WALLEYE LARGEMOUTH BASS, AND BLUEGILL. TWO HYBRID SUNFISH WERE CAPTURED ALSO. WALLEYE, BASS, AND BLUEGILL ARE WELL ABOVE STATE AND LOCAL MEDIANS, PARTICULA- RLY THE BASS AND BLUEGILL. BLUEGILLS ALTHOUGH ABOUT FOR TIMES THE LOCAL MEDIAN ABUNDANCE EXHIBIT GOOD GROWTH AND SIZE DISTRIBUTION. WALLEYES AND LARGEMOUTH BASS ARE ALSO ABOVE LOCAL MEDIAN LEVELS, BUT SURVIVAL AND GROWTH OF THE FISH STOCKED AFTER CHEMICAL REHABILITATION IS VERY GOOD.

WTS, YEB, AND YEP WERE SAMPLED AT NEAR LOCAL MEDAIN LEVELS. BLB WERE LOW IN ABUNDANCE. BLG, LMB, BLC AND WAE WERE SAMPLED AT ABOVE LOCAL MEDIAN ABUNDANCE. BLG WERE TYPICALLY SMALL, WITH A PSD OF 2.3. BLG GROWTH WAS SLOW. ELECTRO- FISHING SAMPLING OF LMB REVEALED SEVERAL SIZE CLASSES BELOW THE MINIMUM SIZE LIMIT OF 16 BASS OVER 16 WERE YEARLING FISH. LMB GROWTH WAS AVERAGE. WAE FROM THE 1986 STOCKING SHOWED AVERAGE GROWTH FOR THE AREA. THE ORIGIN OF THE SNG IS UNKNOWN, HOWEVER, STOCKING BY AN ANGLER OR RESIDENT IS SUSPECTED.

Como Lake is a chronic winterkill lake which exhibits low oxygen levels most winters. The DNR has not stocked Como sice 1950. The present fish population is a result of natural reproduction from fish stocked by unknown persons following a severe winterkill which occured the winter of 1972-73; as indicated by the ages of various species found. Green sunfish and black crappie are present in numbers and weight above the statewide median. Black crappie are exceptionally abundant and appear to consist of year classes of I+, II+, and III+ fish. These fish all exhibit very fast growth. Three fish measuring 4.1, 4.2, and 4.3 inches long were determined to be young of the year. Black bullhead and hybrid sunfish are present in numbers above the statewide median but below it in pounds per set. Black bullhead do not appear to be overpopulated judging from the numbers caught and the length frequency distribution. Goldfish are present in numbers below the local median but above the local median in pounds per set. (Note: the local median is based on catches from only three lakes). Pumkin seed are below the median number and pounds per set. Fish aged were I and II annulus fish showing fast growth.

Como Lake's largemouth bass population is down; 11 bass were sampled by electrofishing in May, 1996. With the exception of 1995, this is below previous levels. These fish ranged from 8 to 16 inches long and averaged 10.5 inches. Only two fish were over 12 inches long and only one over 16 inches. Bluegill were the most abundant fish sampled. Size of bluegill is improved from previous years with over 25% being 6 inches or longer and 5% being at least 7 inches long. 1996 is the first time since 1988 that bluegill over 7 inches long have been sampled, when 1% were at least 7 inches long. Moderate numbers of black crappie are present with most less than 7 inches long, but over 10% 8 inches or longer. Northern pike were sampled for the first time in Como Lake with five fish between 24 and 28 inches long. The yellow perch populaton is up, but are present in only moderate numbers. Lengths of perch ranged from 6.5 to 9 inches. A few walleye remain from the 1986 stocking. Two were captured - these were both between 22 and 23 inches long. Small channel catfish yearlings were stocked in early July of 1996 - two of these were captured. Other species caught in low numbers were black bullhead, hybrid sunfish, white sucker, and golden shiner.
